So, the lognormal distribution seems a nice fit on the observed histogram, but we have some bins, around 400-600 minutes, where the relative frequencies of observed internet usage times are higher than they should be based on the lognormal density function. So are these differences significant or are they just caused by sampling error alone? Let’s see the following hypotheses!

  • \(H_0:\) The true population distribution is lognormal
  • \(H_1:\) The true population distribution is NOT lognormal

So, let’s apply the \(\chi^2\) goodness-of-fit test with deciles (\(k=10\)) now. Due to the deciles, we have \(f^*_j=n/10\), that is \(f^*_j = 1391/10=139.1>5\), so the assumptions of the test are satisfied. We have \(b=2\) again as we estimated \(2\) parameters for the lognormal distribution with MLE: \((\mu,\sigma)\).

lnorm_deciles <- qlnorm(seq(0,1,0.1), meanlog = lnorm_ml$par[1], sdlog = lnorm_ml$par[2])
observed_freq <- table(cut(ess_small$DailyNetUse, breaks = lnorm_deciles))
chi2_result <- chisq.test(observed_freq)
p_value_chi2 <- 1-pchisq(chi2_result$statistic, df = 10-2-1)
p_value_chi2*100 # in percentage format
## X-squared 
##         0

Now, this p-value is quite a fail,as it is practically \(0\), so it is smaller even than \(1\%\). This means that \(H_0\) is rejected on every common significance levels. So the internet usage time distribution is significantly different from lognormal.

If we compare the differences between observed (\(f_j\)) and theoretical (\(f^*_j\)) frequencies, we can see that this significant difference is mainly coming from the fact that we should have about 118 less people with 101-122 minutes of internet usage than we should have in case of a true lognormal distribution, and we should have about 107 more people in the observed sample with 122-146 minutes of internet usage time.

chi2_result$observed-chi2_result$expected
## 
##    (0,59.2] (59.2,80.7]  (80.7,101]   (101,122]   (122,146]   (146,175] 
##       -61.1        33.9        -6.1       117.9      -107.1       -52.1 
##   (175,212]   (212,265]   (265,362]   (362,Inf] 
##        90.9       -46.1        63.9       -34.1

Poisson Example

The \(\chi^2\) goodness-of-fit test can be applied without binning directly on testing the goodness of fit for discrete probability distributions.

We’ve used the CarInsurance_NumberOfClaims sheet of the insurance_examples.xlsx file as an example for the Poisson distribution in Section 5.3 of Chapter 1. Here, we have \(n=400\) observation of insured cars and the NumClaims variable contains the number of accidents (or claims) reported in a year. In Chapter 1, we fitted a \(Poi(\lambda)\) distribution on the NumClaims variable with method of moments. Let’s repeat this process!

num_claims <- readxl::read_excel("insurance_examples.xlsx", sheet = "CarInsurance_NumberOfClaims")
est_lambda <- mean(num_claims$NumClaims)
est_lambda
## [1] 0.71

So, at this point, we assume that the number of claims a year follows a \(Poi(0.71)\) distribution. In Chapter 1, we’ve checked the goodness of fit for our \(Poi(0.71)\) distribution by comparing theoretical \(P(y_i=x)\) probabilities and the relative frequencies for every observed value of the variable in our sample.

empirical_probs <- prop.table(table(num_claims$NumClaims))
variable_values <- as.numeric(names(empirical_probs))
freq_table <- data.frame("variable_values"=variable_values,
                         "empirical_probs" = as.numeric(empirical_probs))
freq_table$theoretical_probs <- dpois(freq_table$variable_values, lambda = est_lambda)
freq_table

Looks like the empirical and theoretical probabilities are quite close to each other, but we have minor differences. So are these differences significant in the true in the unobserved population of cars? Let’s check it with the following hypothesis test.

  • \(H_0:\) The true population distribution is Poisson
  • \(H_1:\) The true population distribution is NOT Poisson

If we apply the \(\chi^2\) goodness-of-fit test, there is no need for binning, as we only have \(k=5\) unique values in our discrete variable as seen in the frequency table given above. The \(f_j\) observed and \(f^*_j\) theoretical frequencies in the sample can be easily calculated by multiplying the empirical_probs and theoretical_probs columns of our freq_table with sample size \(n\) respectively.

observed_freq <- freq_table$empirical_probs * nrow(num_claims)
theoretical_freq <- freq_table$theoretical_probs * nrow(num_claims)

We should check if the \(f^*_j \geq5\) condition of the test is met.

theoretical_freq
## [1] 196.657679 139.626952  49.567568  11.730991   2.082251

Looks like we wouldn’t have at least \(5\) observation in case of \(H_0\) with the value of \(4\), so we merge this category with the \(3\) values to create the minimum of \(5\) theoretical observations in the last category. Logically we consider this last category as \(3+\), i.e. it contains every value \(\geq3\).

observed_freq[4] <- observed_freq[4] + observed_freq[5]
observed_freq <- observed_freq[1:4]

theoretical_freq[4] <- theoretical_freq[4] + theoretical_freq[5]
theoretical_freq <- theoretical_freq[1:4]

cbind(values=0:3, observed=observed_freq, theoretical=theoretical_freq)
##      values observed theoretical
## [1,]      0      191   196.65768
## [2,]      1      150   139.62695
## [3,]      2       46    49.56757
## [4,]      3       13    13.81324

Great, all is set to apply the chisq.test function to calculate the test statistic. We just need to provide the observed \(f_j\) frequencies as usual, and provide the theoretical relative frequencies (so \(f^*_j/n=f^*_j/\sum_j{f^*_j}\)) through the second, p parameter of the function.
The p-value needs to be calculated manually here as well to account for the fact that we estimated \(b=1\) parameter for fitting the Poisson distribution on our observed data, the \(\lambda\). In this case \(k=4\), as we have examined \(f_j\) and \(f^*_j\) values for \(4\) values after the merge: \(j=0,1,2,\geq3\).

chi2_result <- chisq.test(observed_freq, p = theoretical_freq/sum(theoretical_freq))
p_value_chi2 <- 1-pchisq(chi2_result$statistic, df = 4-1-1)
p_value_chi2*100 # in percentage format
## X-squared 
##  53.88253

The p-value is \(47.3\%\), which is higher than even the highest significance level of \(10\%\), so \(H_0\) cannot be rejected on the common \(\alpha\) levels, so we can say that the observed claim distribution is NOT significantly different from \(Poi(0.71)\). Which is nice, as we can confidently use the Poisson distribution to estimate the occurrence of claim numbers that are higher than the maximum of what’s observed in our sample.

7.2. Kolmogorov-Smirnov Goodness-of-Fit Tests

An alternative for the \(\chi^2\) test if our numeric variable \(Y\) has continuous distribution is the Kolmogorov-Smirnov test. Here, you don’t need to bin your continuous variable before applying the test, like we did with the \(\chi^2\) test, as this test applies the continuous distributions’ cumulative distribution function \(F(x)\) directly. If You need a reminder on cumulative distribution functions, see Section 2.2 of Chapter 1.

The \(H_0\) and \(H_1\) of the test are the same as for the \(\chi^2\) test:

  • \(H_0\) states that our observed variable \(Y\) follows the specified continuous distribution in the unobserved population
  • \(H_1\) stat that our observed variable \(Y\) has a significantly different distribution than the one stated in \(H_0\)

So, in general if we want to see if our observed variable \(Y\) follows a specific continuous distribution (normal, exponential, etc.), we need to take the fitted probability distribution’s theoretical cumulative distribution function \(F(x)\) and we compare it with the cumulative relative frequencies of the observed sample denoted as \(F_n(x)\). So, \(F_n(x)\) is simply defined as follows: \[F_n(x)=\frac{\text{number of observations} \leq x}{n}\]

According to the Kolmogorov-Smirnov (KS) test statistic we compare \(F(x)\) and \(F_n(x)\) at their largest possible difference (in the supreme point of their absolute differences along the possible \(x\) values the variable \(Y\) can take): \[D_n=\sup_{x}{|F(x)-F_n(x)|}\]

This is illustrated on the following plot. The red line is \(F(x)\), the blue line is \(F_n(x)\), and the black arrow is the KS statistic ic itself.

The p-value is derived from the Kolmogorov distribution in a right tailed way (since the best case of the test statistic for \(H_0\) is \(D_n=0\) of course, and we need to decrease the p-value if \(D_n>0\)). This is a special distribution developed just for this test alone, and due to the providence of the machine spirit, it is implemented in base R, so we don’t really burden ourselves with its density function and other stuff. You can see it on the link before if You want. :)

So now that we know how the KS test works, let’s see it in action and examine with this test as well whether the BMI values in the Hungarian ESS sample follow a normal distribution. So we have the following hypotheses.

  • \(H_0:\) The true population distribution is normal
  • \(H_1:\) The true population distribution is NOT normal

To obtain the test statistic and p-value, we need to apply the ks.test function in base R. The first parameter of the function is the observed numerical variable and the second is the R code for the theoretical cumulative distribution function (\(F(x)\)) of the distribution assumed in \(H_0\). So, we need the p prefixed function of the normal distribution here. Thankfully the function is smart enough to estimate the parameters of the fitted distribution (so \(\mu\) and \(\sigma\) in this case) in the background via maximum likelihood method.

ess_small <- ess[!is.na(ess$BMI),c("idno", "BMI")]
ks.test(ess_small$BMI, "pnorm")
## 
##  Asymptotic one-sample Kolmogorov-Smirnov test
## 
## data:  ess_small$BMI
## D = 1, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: two-sided

Our p-value is smaller than \(2.2 \times 10^{-16}\), so this is a rejection of \(H_0\) on every common significance levels. :( So, in this case the test says that the BMI distribution is significantly different from the normal distribution even on \(\alpha=1\%\).
This is a bit of a contradiction with the results of the \(\chi^2\) test where on \(\alpha=1\%\), the normality \(H_0\) couldn’t be rejected.
The reason behind this contradiction is the fact that the Kolmogorov-Smirnov test is even more in favor of \(H_1\) than the \(\chi^2\) test. In the \(\chi^2\) test, we examine the differences of observed and theoretical distribution in more then one points, in \(k\) points to be exact. However, the KS test examines this difference in one point alone, where the theoretical and observed distribution shows the largest amount of difference. So, there is not even a minimal level of control on the other parts of the distribution that we have in the \(\chi^2\) test. This causes more Type I errors in the KS test, especially in large sample sizes. So, I advise using \(\chi^2\) test even for continuous distributions. The extra work with forming the bins based on quantiles usually worth it as we can compare the obserevd and theoretical distributions in more than 1 point this way. Simulation studies show that a \(\chi^2\) test with deciles or quintiles as bins have more power (i.e. less Type II errors) than the KS test as well.

Now, we have several legends surrounding the name of the Kolmogorov-Smirnov test. The official version is that it is named after Soviet mathematicians Andrey Kolmogorov and Nikolai Smirnov, who developed it in the 1930s at their comfy stay in Hotel Gulag.
However, the other version is that Andrey Kolmogorov got so drunk on Smirnov vodka that he came up with this test that has such an unfavorable Type I error rate compared to the \(\chi^2\) test. What is the truth, we’ll never know. :)

7.3. \(\chi^2\) Test of Homogeneity

Let’s examine the statement that, in the entire Hungarian population, males and females have the same BMI distribution. In other words, the distribution of BMI between males and females is homogeneous.

We describe this base assumption using the following null and alternative hypothesis pair:

  • \(H_0:\) The two groups (males and females) have identical BMI distributions in the population
  • \(H_1:\) The two groups (males and females) have different BMI distributions in the population

To compute this, we first need to bin the BMI values according to some quantiles. Let’s use the deciles here. First, we calculate the empirical deciles of BMI for the entire sample.

ess_small <- ess[!is.na(ess$BMI),c("idno", "BMI", "Sex")]
BMI_deciles <- quantile(ess_small$BMI, probs=seq(0,1,0.1))
BMI_deciles
##       0%      10%      20%      30%      40%      50%      60%      70% 
## 16.00366 21.30395 22.77319 23.98687 25.12783 26.12245 26.98962 28.04038 
##      80%      90%     100% 
## 29.38776 31.25000 40.00000

Next, we use the cut function to split the variable according to the decile values given in the breaks parameter. Then we use the table function to count the frequencies within these intervals.

ess_small$binned_BMI <- cut(ess_small$BMI, breaks = BMI_deciles)
table(ess_small$binned_BMI)
## 
##   (16,21.3] (21.3,22.8]   (22.8,24]   (24,25.1] (25.1,26.1]   (26.1,27] 
##         203         200         200         201         205         196 
##     (27,28]   (28,29.4] (29.4,31.2]   (31.2,40] 
##         203         203         204         193

Great, we truly have roughly \(10\%\) of the \(n=2009\) observations in the new bins of BMI variable.

To compute the test statistic, we need a contingency frequency table (crosstab) — just like the one we created for stacked bar plots in Section 4.4 of Prelude 2.

This table shows the frequencies of each BMI decile (binned_BMI) for both the male and female groups.

crosstab <- table(ess_small[, c("binned_BMI", "Sex")])
crosstab
##              Sex
## binned_BMI    Female Male
##   (16,21.3]      169   34
##   (21.3,22.8]    145   55
##   (22.8,24]      114   86
##   (24,25.1]      117   84
##   (25.1,26.1]    122   83
##   (26.1,27]       85  111
##   (27,28]        107   96
##   (28,29.4]      107   96
##   (29.4,31.2]    121   83
##   (31.2,40]      119   74

So for example, we observe that \(34\) males in our sample with BMI lower than \(21.3\).

Now let’s look at the proportions of BMI deciles within each gender! We use the prop.table function with the second parameter set to 2, because we want to calculate proportions within the columns (2nd dimension) of the contingency table (i.e., percentage by column total).

prop.table(crosstab,2)
##              Sex
## binned_BMI        Female       Male
##   (16,21.3]   0.14013267 0.04239401
##   (21.3,22.8] 0.12023217 0.06857855
##   (22.8,24]   0.09452736 0.10723192
##   (24,25.1]   0.09701493 0.10473815
##   (25.1,26.1] 0.10116086 0.10349127
##   (26.1,27]   0.07048093 0.13840399
##   (27,28]     0.08872305 0.11970075
##   (28,29.4]   0.08872305 0.11970075
##   (29.4,31.2] 0.10033167 0.10349127
##   (31.2,40]   0.09867330 0.09226933

So for instance, \(12\%\) of females have a BMI in the range of \((21.3,22.8]\), while only \(6.8\%\) of males have the same healthy level of BMI.

But are these differences in BMI proportions between genders just due to sampling error? \(\rightarrow\) Hypothesis test! :)

Our test statistic is the following: \[\sum_{i=1}^{r}\sum_{j=1}^{c}\frac{(f_{ij}-f^*_{ij})^2}{f^*_{ij}}\sim\chi^2((r-1)(c-1))\]

Under \(H_0\), the distribution of this test statistic — based on many samples — follows the \(\chi^2((r-1)(c-1))\) distribution, where \(r\) is the number of rows (BMI bins), and \(c\) is the number of columns (genders) in the contingency table.
Here, \(f^*_{ij}\) is the expected frequency — it tells us how many observations of BMI level \(i\) we’d expect in gender \(j\) if the distribution of \(i\) were identical across all \(j\) groups. In other words, the homogeneity \(H_0\) states also means that BMI and gender are INDEPENDENT as random variables \(\rightarrow\) the grouping variable \(j\) does not influence the distribution of \(i\), and hence it is the same (homogeneous) in all groups.

Thus, the expected frequencies can be computed using the multiplication rule for independent probabilities, which states in case of independent \(i\) and \(j\) the probability of the \(ij\) pair occurring together is the multiplication of the probabilities that \(i\) and \(j\) occurs separately: \[f^*_{ij}=\frac{f_{i.}f_{.j}}{n}\]

Where \(f_{i.}\) and \(f_{.j}\) are the total counts of the values \(i\) and \(j\) in the sample respectively — also known as the marginal frequencies.

We need to note here too that technically the \(H_0\) and \(H_1\) pairs of this test of homogeneity state the following:

  • \(H_0: f_{ij}=f^*_{ij} ,\forall i,j\)
  • \(H_1: \exists i,j: f_{ij} \neq f^*_{ij}\)

So, even if in one \(i\) and \(j\) pairing, we have a significant difference in the observed frequency \(f_{ij}\) and the theoretical frequency \(f^*_{ij}\) under \(H_0\), then \(H_0\) is rejected, no matter that in the rest of the pairs, the observed frequencies fit to the homogeneous distribution assumed in \(H_0\).
That is why this \(\chi^2\) test of homogeneity also very much favors \(H_1\), as it is a very strong statement here as well.

After calculating the test statistic, the p-value is computed in a right-tailed manner — just like in goodness-of-fit tests.

We can calculate the test statistic and p-value using the built-in chisq.test function. We only need the contingency table (frequency crosstab) as input — the function can calculate the degrees of freedom automatically.

chisq.test(crosstab)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  crosstab
## X-squared = 91.676, df = 9, p-value = 7.503e-16

In our case, the p-value is \(7.503e-16\), which is smaller than even the lowest typical significance level of \(1\%\). So in the population (i.e., outside of our sample), the BMI distribution of males and females can be considered DIFFERENT.
In other words, the observed difference in BMI proportions between males and females in our sample is likely not due to sampling error alone — i.e. statistically significant.

The expected element in the result list returned by chisq.test is the contingency table that would occur if \(H_0\) were true (i.e., if the two groups were to have the same BMI distribution). We can verify using prop.table that in this theoretical contingency table, the proportions within columns = genders are indeed roughly equal — just as \(H_0\) states.

homogenity_result <- chisq.test(crosstab)
prop.table(homogenity_result$expected,2)
##              Sex
## binned_BMI        Female       Male

##   (21.3,22.8] 0.09960159 0.09960159
##   (22.8,24]   0.09960159 0.09960159

##   (31.2,40]   0.09611554 0.09611554

As \(H_0\) is rejected, it would be interesting to see where the observed values \(f_{ij}\) differ most from the expected \(f^*_{ij}\).

By examining the differences \(f_{ij} - f^*_{ij}\), we can clearly see, for example, that there are about \(47\) fewer males in the lowest BMI category of the sample than we would expect under independence (\(H_0\)), and there are about \(33\) more males with BMI in the range of 26.1-27 (the obese category) than expected under \(H_0\). So, no way to sugarcoat it: Hungarian males are way more obese than females. Time to hit the gym or go for a run. :)

7.4. Kolmogorov-Smirnov Test of Homogeneity

The Kolmogorov–Smirnov (KS) test may also be used to test whether two underlying continuous probability distributions differ significantly. So, it has a version that mirrors the \(\chi^2\) test of homogeneity for continuous numerical \(Y\) variables specifically. This version is also called as the two-sample KS test since we are comparing the distribution of the variable \(Y\) along two groups \(A\) and \(B\), and the two groups are treated as two independent samples in this case. Meaning that the groups mustn’t overlap: if someone is in group \(A\), they cannot be in group \(B\) as well. The hypotheses of this test is the same as for the \(\chi^2\) test of homogeneity.

  • \(H_0:\) The two groups (\(A\) and \(B\)) have identical distributions for the variable \(Y\) in the population
  • \(H_1:\) The two groups (\(A\) and \(B\)) have different distributions for the variable \(Y\) in the population

For the test statistic we just need the cumulative relative frequencies of the two groups \(F_A(x)\) and \(F_B(x)\). Both are defined the same way as \(F_n(x)\) in Section 7.2. And by the KS logic, the test statistic is the supremum of differences between the two groups’ cumulative relative frequencies along the possible \(x\) values the variable \(Y\) can take. \[D_n=\sup_{x}{|F_A(x)-F_B(x)|}\]

The p-value is derived from the same Kolmogorov distribution in a right tailed way as it was for the one-sample case in Section 7.2.

Now that we know how the KS test of homogeneity works, let’s apply it to test if males and females have a significantly different BMI distributions in the unobserved population. So, the two hypotheses are the same as in the \(\chi^2\) test of homogeneity.

  • \(H_0:\) The two groups (males and females) have identical BMI distributions in the population
  • \(H_1:\) The two groups (males and females) have different BMI distributions in the population

The test statistic and p-value are obtained with the same ks.test function as before, but it is now used with the same ~ signed way as the oneway.test in Section 6.2. So, we need the following syntax: numerical variable ~ variable that defines the two groups. And in the data parameter we give the name of the data frame where these two variables live.

ess_small <- ess[!is.na(ess$BMI),c("idno", "BMI", "Sex")]
ks.test(BMI~Sex, data = ess_small)
## 
##  Asymptotic two-sample Kolmogorov-Smirnov test
## 
## data:  BMI by Sex
## D = 0.15657, p-value = 1.101e-10
## alternative hypothesis: two-sided

In our case, the p-value is \(1.101e-10\), which is smaller than even the lowest typical significance level of \(1\%\). So in the population (i.e., outside of our sample), the BMI distribution of males and females can be considered DIFFERENT.
This comes as no surprise, since we rejected this same \(H_0\) with the \(\chi^2\) test too. And even in this two-sample case, the KS test has the same drawback compared to the \(\chi^2\) test as it had in the one-sample (or goodness-of-fit) case. Namely, the Kolmogorov-Smirnov test is even more in favor of \(H_1\) than the \(\chi^2\) test. In the \(\chi^2\) test, we examine the differences of the two groups’ distribution in more then one points, in \(k\) points to be exact. However, the KS test examines this difference in one point alone, where the two groups’ distribution shows the largest amount of difference. So, there is not even a minimal level of control on the other parts of the distribution that we have in the \(\chi^2\) test. This causes more Type I errors in the KS test, especially in large sample sizes. So, I advise using \(\chi^2\) test even for continuous distributions in this case as well for the same reasons described in Section 7.2.
